Framing the Problem

The goal of this report is to develop a univariate predictive model for median house value using basic demographic and housing-related features. Specifically, we will explore the relationship between median house value and each of the following independent variables: median income, population, number of households

In[51]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score, mean_absolute_error
import numpy as np

Getting the Data

We will be using the California Housing Prices Dataset on Kaggle , which contains lots of information from the 1990 California census. This data includes features like median income, population, number of households, and median house value for different districts in California.

Visualize the Relationships

In order to understand this data fully lets go through some plots with three independent variables and the dependent variable median house value.

Median Income vs. Median House Value

In[55]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.scatterplot(x='median_income', y='median_house_value', data=df)
plt.title('Median Income vs. Median House Value')
plt.xlabel('Median Income')
plt.ylabel('Median House Value')
plt.show()

Interpretation: You can see a clear positive linear relationship between these two variables suggesting that Median Income will be a fantastic predictor, especially because we are running a linear regression model.

Population vs. Median House Value

In[56]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.scatterplot(x='population', y='median_house_value', data=df)
plt.title('Population vs. Median House Value')
plt.xlabel('Population')
plt.ylabel('Median House Value')
plt.show()

Interpretation: There is clearly a weak linear relationship here, if any at all, the points do not seem to follow a trend based on the population at all. This can mean that population is most likely not a good indicator of house value.

Number of Households vs. Median House Value

In[57]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.scatterplot(x='households', y='median_house_value', data=df)
plt.title('Number of Households vs. Median House Value')
plt.xlabel('Number of Households')
plt.ylabel('Median House Value')
plt.show()

Interpretation: Here we can see that there is a slight positive linear trend between the two variables starting at the very bottom of the plot. However, the dispersion of points beyond that is much too high to consider this a strong relationship. This is another factor that is likely to be a weak predictor of house value.

Variable Descriptions:

Median House Value

  • This is simply a variable that represents median price of houses within a certain area
  • This is the target variable in our regression model
  • Has an approximate range of 15000 to 500001, this is actually very bad for the data selection because any value above this ceiling is reported as the max of 500001, this is going to skew the results of our regression

Median Income

  • Represents Median income (tens of thousands of dollars)
  • Ranges from 0 to 15 inclusive
  • So far this variables has shown the strongest positive linear relationship with the median house value

Population

  • Indicates the population of people in the certain area
  • Very high fluctuation in the range depending on location
  • So far there is no clear correlation between population and median house value

Number of Households

  • Represents the number of houses in the area
  • There is signifcant variation in the range of the variable
  • Indicates a very weak positive linear trend but is too weak to indicate anything signifcant

Begin the Linear Regression

Code for Median Income vs Median House Value

In[58]:
# Collect applicable data variables
X_income = df[['median_income']]
y = df['median_house_value']

# Create and fit the model
model_income = LinearRegression()
model_income.fit(X_income, y)

# Predict
y_pred_income = model_income.predict(X_income)

# Evaluation 
slope_income = model_income.coef_[0]
intercept_income = model_income.intercept_
mse_income = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred_income)
mae_income = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred_income)
r2_income = r2_score(y, y_pred_income)

Code for Population vs Median House Value

In[59]:
# Collect applicable variables
X_pop = df[['population']]
y = df['median_house_value']

Code for Number of Households vs Median House Value

In[60]:
# Collect applicable variables
X_households = df[['households']]
y = df['median_house_value']

# Create and fit the model
model_households = LinearRegression()
model_households.fit(X_households, y)

# Predict
y_pred_households = model_households.predict(X_households)

# Evaluation 
slope_households = model_households.coef_[0]
intercept_households = model_households.intercept_

mae_households = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred_households)
r2_households = r2_score(y, y_pred_households)

Summarize the Results

In this Lab we ran linear regressions on three different variates to determine their relationship with the dependent variate Median House Value.

Below I have displayed a table that sums up the results in a concise manner:

Feature Slope Intercept MSE (lower = better) MAE (lower = better) R Score (higher = better)
Median Income High + Moderate Lowest Lowest Highest
Population Small - High Highest Highest Very Low
Households Small + Moderate Mid Mid Moderate

We demonstrated the following:

  • Median Income showed the only strong positive linear relationship with Median House Value

  • Population and Number of Households showed a very linear relationship and cannot be said to have any impact on the Median House Value

Key Insights:

This biggest issue with this lab was actually the data itself. The Median House Value having a ceiling was a major issue in terms of data selection. This means that any data above the ceiling (500001) will be written as 500001, this will heavily skew the data because in this case there are many points that are at this ceiling which will underestimate high valued properties.

The second scatter plots can confirm that the only positive linear trend that had any accuracy was the Median Income variate. This result is inline with the original scatterplot as well as all the interpretation we wrote while discussing the previous scatterplot.
